tweet: Party like its 1999: S&P 500, Nasdaq Composite & 100 close at record highs.
In case you missed it: Wall St analysts are bullish as they have been in nearly 2 decades. Bullish tone comes as S&P 500 and Nasdaq Composite near or at record levels.

Facebook reported the fastest revenue growth in over five years, bolstered by a hot ad market. The social media giant warned it could be hard to top these boom times. Says revenue growth to slow this year; shares drop 3% in after-hours trading.
Bitcoin on course $40k as Amazon appears to dip its toe into Crypto World. An Amazon job posting published online last week seeks a “Digital Currency and Blockchain Product Lead.”

7 Big Tech stocks Facebook, Apple, Netflix, Google, Microsoft, Amazon, Nvidia accounted for ~130% of latest increase in S&P 500 mkt cap. Still FANGMAN stocks have not yet taken out their peak rel to S&P 500. Now account for 25.8% of S&P500 mkt cap below peak of Sep2020 at 27.3%.
In case you missed it: Combined mkt cap of FANGMAN (Facebook, Apple, Netflix, Google, Microsoft, Amazon, Nvidia) has topped $10tn for the first time ever.
Just to put things into perspective: S&P trades at ATH: 179 trading days have passed since the last 5% S&P 500 drawdown.

Dow jumps more than 200 points closing >35k for first time ever, all major averages hit record closes on blowout earnings. Nasdaq adds 1% Fri; Leaps 2.8% for week About 87% of the S&P 500 comps reporting results so far this season have beaten Wall St estimates, acc to Bloomberg.

Dow jumps above 35,000 as retail sales top expectations. Retail sales rose 0.6% in June, as the economy reopened more broadly and auto dealers navigated supply disruptions. Economists were expecting another decrease after May's 1.3% drop.

Good morning from Italy, a stock mkt developing country. Although Italy is still 8th largest econ in world, all Italian shares combined are worth just $722bn. That's less than the mkt cap of Facebook ($998bn). At times, even Tesla was worth more, selling just 200k cars a quarter

S&P 500, Dow, Nasdaq close at record highs, rebounding from 1d slide. Friday’s comeback brought all three majors averages into the green for the week. The Dow rose 0.25% for the week. The S&P 500 and Nasdaq gained 0.4% and 0.4% since Monday, respectively.

The $5.4 Trillion bet on the S&P 500: Acc to S&P Dow Jones Indices, a record $5.4tn is in ETFs that passively track the S&P 500. At the end of 2008 during the financial crisis, there was just $915bn worth of assets indexed to the S&P 500.
Wall St powers through the first half of 2021 w/US stocks at record highs. S&P 500 has the 2nd best start of a year since 1998.   (Chart via BBG)
After Jeff Bezos: the changing of the guard at Amazon. Andy Jassy takes over as the $1.7tn company comes under intense political and regulatory scrutiny.

History says stocks could be due for selloff: S&P500 bottomed on Mar23, 2020, which means we’re 3mths into Year2 of bull mkt. Since 1945, bull mkts saw avg drawdown of 10% during Yr2 – ranged from -5% to -16%. Since Mar23, 2021, S&P seen max drawdown of 4%

Hey guys, don't miss our daily  Podcast AAA where we talk about Facebook, which has joined the 1 TRILLION DOLLAR CLUB. We explain what the advantage is of having a mkt cap of >$1tn. After all, there are only 16 countries w/GDP of >$1tn. So listen in!

Facebook joined the $1 TRILLION CLUB after comp wins dismissal of US, states’ monopoly lawsuits. Judge says FTC failed to meet burden Facebook has monopoly. FTC can refile complaint within 30 days, judge says in ruling.

Short sellers are back as S&P 500 has hit new heights & on track to post one of best first halves on record. Bearish bets on SPDR S&P 500 ETF have climbed to 5% of its shares outstanding, from <2% at start of this year, BBG reports. Demand for protection against losses is rising.

S&P 500 closed week at another ATH, printing best weekly performance since Feb, albeit shallow breadth of rally may be a warning signal, BBG’s Ye Xie writes. 48% of S&P 500 members trading >50d moving average, the lowest percentage since 1999, suggesting the rally lacks momentum.

The S&P 500 may have hit a new ATH today at 4,277 points, +13.8% YTD, but if you put the index in relation to Fed's balance sheet, it is trading at the same level as in 2008, so equities have traded sideways since 2008, basically counteracting balance sheet expansion.
The huge get bigger: Apple, Microsoft, Amazon, and Alphabet are all at or near a $2tn valuation. Facebook is the most likely next member of the trillion-dollar club.
Dip buyers help S&P 500 open the week 1.4% higher w/95% of members up, the 3rd time >90% threshold this year and the largest share since April 8, 2020, BBG has calculated.
It's the liquidity, stupid! S&P has dropped in tandem w/global liquidity which has shrunk by $1tn this week.

Just put things into perspective: Germany's Dax has dropped 1.6% this week. The combined mkt cap of all 30 Dax Blue Chips has fallen to $1.65tn, also b/c the Euro has lost >2% against the dollar this week. Is now again lower than that of the US big 3: Apple, Microsoft, Amazon.

Fed's Powell tries to sound a bit more dovish Discussing liftoff now would be highly premature. Powell says this meeting was the 'talking about talking about' meeting. Dow pares some losses, US 10y yields come off today's highs.

Good Morning from Germany where the benchmark index Dax has closed at fresh ATH on Fri. But the combined mkt cap of all 30 Dax Blue Chips is lower than that of US tech giants such as Apple or Microsoft. Dax mkt cap is on a par w/Amazon, which has not moved up since last Aug.
S&P 500 Index finally posted a new record, shrugging off inflation fears.

S&P 500 ended the week 0.7% higher at 4,229.89 less than 0.2% from its ATH while fear index VIX near the pre-pandemic low and that before a week with important US inflation figures is coming up.

BOOM! S&P 500 gain after 5 months bodes well for next 7, if history is any guide. Since 1950, gains of 10% to 15% in the first 5mths of the year were followed by gains of avg 11.5% from June through Dec. (via BBG)

Goldman says proposed US capital gains tax hike will limit S&P 500 upside. Estimates $1+ tn in unrealized cap gains for wealthiest US households, equal to 3% of US mkt cap & roughly 30% of avg monthly S&P 500 trading vol. Past tax hikes have been associated w/declines in prices.

Italy’s credit rating unch for now by S&P at BBB, 2 notches above junk, stable outlook although debt is seen rising to historic record of 160% of GDP this yr. S&P sees Italy econ expanding by 4.7% in 2021 and 4.2% in 2022. Mario Draghi govt passed €40 billion worth of stimulus.

OUCH! Dow plunges 400 points on fears of higher capital gains taxes. BBG reports that Biden is planning a capital gains tax hike to as high as 43.4% for wealthy Americans. Proposal would hike capital gains rate to 39.6% for those earning >$1mln, up from 20% currently.

As the first day goes, so goes the year? S&P 500 staged an impressive rebound off its earlier lows. Index wound up climbing ~43 points or ~1.7% trough-to-peak as investors shrugging off doom data from China.
US stocks post worst year in a decade as Dow Jones falls 5.6% in 2018
Market strategist who nailed S&P 500 this year has a Fed theory. Deutsche Bank’s Kocic predicted a drop to below 2,400. Average year-end stock target at start of 2018 was 2,855.

Good morning from Germany, where stocks have lost $500bn in market cap this year w/benchmark index Dax -18.3%ytd, Mid-Cap index MDax -17.6%ytd. All German stocks are now worth only $1.9tn, less than world's Top 3, Microsoft ($776bn), Apple ($741bn) and Google ($724bn), combined.
Wall Street slips, but stocks mark 1st positive week in Dec. Dow closed Fri session 0.3% lower, but ended shortened trading week 2.8% higher. Now down 9.7% in Dec.

Asia stocks limp into year-end after miraculous US rebound. Dow rose >800 points in <2hours. US govt remained shutdown, could have effects on consumer & business sentiment. Japan 10y ylds fall <0 first time since 2017, Gold continues to rise as traders looked for havens from vol.

Stocks and bond yields trade in lock-step, suggesting widely anticipated large month-end and quarter-end pension rebalancing flows. S&P 500 erases 2.8% drop in biggest reversal since 2010, while US 10y yields initially had fallen to 2.73% before climbing back to 2.78%.

Another historic day on Wall St: Dow Jones turned green in a late jump after trading negative for most of the day. The index ends 260 points higher, erases 611 point drop, swang 870 points peak-to-trough.
Dow resumes downtrend as epic rally falters. Trades 1.3% lower, unable to add to Wednesday's 5% surge.
Dow Industrials post first-ever 1,000 Point gain in a session. But the joy may be short-lived: Next year is when the trade war chickens will finally come home to roost.
US stocks surge; Dow adds a whopping 1,084 Points.

With Trump preaching Buy the Dip, stocks look cheapest in years. S&P 500 at cheapest relative to forward earnings since 2013. American stocks are also looking less of an outlier versus other advanced markets than earlier this year.
US stocks rebound from bear brink w/ Dow up >400 points as Trump preaching buy the dip.

Shares of Facebook rise as short-seller Citron calls FB as "2019 S&P stock of the year", and says while & media has reported on one scandal after the other, the truth is revenues and user base has seen little impact. Facebook not more evil than Altria
Dow dives 600 points to below 22,000, S&P 500 enters bear market - worst Christmas Eve ever
Fear Index Vix jumps by 15% as stock market rout deepens w/ S&P plunges to lowest level since May2017.

Bad year fur bulls: Wells Fargo cut estimates for stocks next year on concern the Fed is making a pol mistake that will throttle econ. Strategist Chris Harvey cut his 2019 year-end target for S&P 500 to 2,665 from 3,079. Harvey now least bullish strategist

In case you missed it: Dow has formed a death cross as 50d moving average has fallen below its 200d moving average. In past 10yrs, Dow formed a death cross 5 times and fell an avg 2.1% in next 20 days. It declined 3 times for an avg loss of 4.9%. (BBG)
US stocks suffer worst week in a decade. Dow lost 6.8% and 1,656 points on the week. It was its worst percentage drop since Oct2008.

Asia stocks following ongoing selloff in US w/participation subdued ahead of holiday season. Japan dropped deeper into bear mkt. S&P 500 tumbled -1.6%, is now down -10.6% in Dec as trade war between US & China escalated further amid US accusations of hacking. Bitcoin stable >$4k.

Wall St continues to fall as there is 0 appetite to step in and buy. S&P 500 drops to lowest since Sep, now -7.7%ytd. Stocks may be very oversold & sentiment is awful but unfortunately the twin vacuums of news and liquidity are making for a toxic environment right now, JPM says.

Looks like someone is panicking: US Treasury Sec Mnuchin says market drop ‘Overblown‘ as S&P 500 on course to  have it’s worst year since GFC. He downplays supply concerns in bond market amid Fed runoff.
Risk barometer AUDJPY hit hard as Fed less dovish than expected. Most risk assets hit after Fed w/ Dow went from >300 up to 350 down. Emerging market assets lower on global growth fears.

Stocks tumble on deepening fears of Fed mistake. Japan enters bear mkt as Topix slides 21% from Jan high, S&P 500 hits 15mth low after Fed Chair Powell disappointed excessively dovish mkt expectations. US 10y ylds drop to 2.75%, Oil continues downtrend, Bitcoin stable at $3.7k.

Markets revolt as steadfast Powell downplays recent sell-off. S&P 500 careens to 15mth low as Fed chairman speaks. Dollar firms and Treasury yields tumble on latest policy move. Credit spreads jump in Risk-Off move.
S&P 500 closed at lowest level since Sep. „The Wed FOMC meeting was the SPX’s last hope and the decision wound up snuffing out whatever hope existed for 2018," JPM says.
The Dow’s 381-Point gain turned into a 500-Point loss as the times of the Fed put seem over.
Stocks turn deeper into the red. Dow now down 250 points as Powell not as dovish as expected.
Dow Jones Industrial pares gains as Fed not as dovish as expected.

Markets fear a 'Black December' as a bad omen. December is usually the 2nd best month of the year. BUT S&P 500 on track to post it's worst December since 1931. The crash of 1987 or the fin crisis of 2008 was preceded by a 'Black December.'   via

Just to put things into perspective. The 12.6% selloff in S&P 500 in Q4 2018 would be the 9th largest historically, UBS has calculated. Only Great Depression, Pearl Harbor/WWII, '87 crash and '08 crisis worse.

S&P 500 ends flat in a volatile day ahead of Fed meeting. Started the Tuesday session w/a solid bounce but faded throughout the day. Index swang >40 points peak-to-trough before closing about unchanged. 'Sentiment is as awful as ever and most just want 2018 to end,' JPM says.

Asia stocks slide following another sell-off on Wall St that sent S&P 500 to lowest since Oct 2017 as global growth worries deepen, investors readied for Fed rate hike and China President Xi's speech disappointing markets. US 10y yields drop to 2.85%, WTI extends decline <$50.

S&P 500 plunges to lowest since Oct2017 w/no sign of Santa Rally. Focus has shifted dramatically away from exogenous issues (trade, politics) towards something more germane to stocks & risk sentiment: growth, JPM says. Trade backdrop better than few mths, but it may be too late.
Ouch! Dow dives another 500 points. Now down 4.6%ytd.
Fear Index Vix jumps 16% as S&P500 heading for new 2018 low on Fed rate-hike fear. Investors worry that another hike could bee too much for the economy and stock mkt to handle.
Ouch! Wall St plunges before Fed meeting. S&P 500 on track to post it's worst Dec in nearly 90yrs.
Unfortunately, Instagram/FB is more successful than Western Union!

After 11% drop from its high in Sep, S&P 500 trading now at 15.5x expected earnings, lowest in 3yrs. But whether it's cheap depends on your time frame, RTRS says. Looks only cheap compared to 20y average but expensive compared to 10y avg.

Dow closed lower after early rally faded. Impetus for initial lift came out of China, w/the auto tariff cut headlines. But there are countervailing forces, including the US-China tech/IP war along w/perceived Washington dysfunction, JPM writes.

Don’t get too scared by flattening yield curve: S&P 500 didn’t peak for >19mths, on avg, after yield curve inverted. On avg, it gained >22% before reaching its high point. Time between inversion & recession arriving can be as long as 765 days.
Facebook has lost >$200bn in mkt cap since summer. Slate Money on the Facebook crisis and what this has to do w/Sandberg and Harvard Business School.
TROUBLE? S&P 500 drops 4.6% in worst week since March, producing a ‘death cross’ feared by investors which is when the index’s 50-day moving average fell below its 200-day average.
Apple and Google erase their gains for the year
US stocks resumed their decline Friday, sending S&P 500 down 4.6% for the week, the worst on a closing basis since Mar, and back into negative territory for the year. (BBG)

Stocks trading lower following terrible lead from Wall St BUT bourses off their lows and S&P Future up after China pledged to quickly implement some steps on trade in wake of G20 summit. Bond rally continues w/Bund ylds drop to 0.25%. Dollar Index >97, Oil lower, Bitcoin at $3.8k

Dow Jones sank almost 800 points or 3.1%, ended the day near the low for 2 main reasons: the lack of substantive agreements in Argentina between Trump and Xi and the going yield curve flattening, which is exacerbating ongoing growth fears.
Dow now down >600points
Ouch! Dow drops >500points on recession fears and as investors reconsider trade truce between US and China.
Big bull calls for markets at year-end suddenly look less crazy. S&P 500 needs another rally of 7% to hit the Street’s target. Trade-war ceasefire, Fed pause, end of oil rout now in sight.

Global stocks have gained $1.6tn in mkt cap this week (on light participation & conviction) as investors reacted to strong Black Friday sales & dovish tilt from Fed which allows US indices to outperform. BUT all major global indices remain below 200d MAs (except Dow & Nikkei).

The comeback of a written off tech dinosaurs: Microsoft has dethroned Apple, now more valuable than Apple for 1st time since 2010. Before that, last time 2 comps switched places was in 1989. Why this must take care of us, Slate Money explains us this week
Dow Jones saw its biggest gains since March after Fed Chair Powell said interest rates are "just below" neutral for the economy.
Dow jumps almost 500points following dovish Fed speech.
Historical moment: Microsoft pushes Apple from the top spot, for the first time since 2010. Microsoft now worth $819bn while Apple's mkt cap has dropped to $816bn.

Apple shares drop in after-hours trading after US President Trump says he would put tariffs on rest of Chinese imports if negotiations at G20 were unsuccessful. Tariffs could also be placed on iPhones imported from China. 'I can make it 10%, & people could stand that very easily'

Chart of doom: Smart Money Index - leading indicator for S&P500 - has collapsed. Index measures tendency for smart investors to sell into usual initial euphoria at mkt open & buy position back in 30 mins before close. Doesn't work when BEARS begin to dominate market. (via SG)
You are right. Cyprus has been investment grade at Fitch and S&P for a while now!

Facebook has problems. Breaking it up would help. It’s a monopoly, having either bought or crushed most competitors. It stifles innovation, potential startups can’t get capital if venture capitalists think they might wind up as Facebook roadkill.   $FB
Dow erases 200-point gain as Apple falls. Liquidity and attendance were super thin owing to the Thanksgiving holiday and this played big a part in the late-day fade.
Thx, pls use Google Translator or Deepl

Wall St. sank across the board. Dow falls 552 points. Nasdaq drops to lowest since Apr. There wasn’t specific fundamental driver for Tues swoon, tech has been imploding for weeks: Each tick lower in tech provides further impetus for the fund community to broadly de-risk, JPM says
Dow drops another 400 points, erases 2018 gains as tech shares keep falling.
Facebook shares drop to lowest since Feb 2017 on massive PR backlash. $FB

With Facebook at "war," Mark Zuckerberg adopts aggressive style that drove out several top executives and created tensions with COO Sheryl Sandberg. Facebook shares have dropped 23% in value since Jan.
S&P, Dow advance on trade optimism: Trump says US may not impose more tariffs on China
The Trump put: Wall St jumps on Trump trade comments. Dow rises almost 1% as Trump appeared to signal a willingness to reach a deal with China at this month’s G-20 summit.
Facebook morale, already hurt by share drop, suffers another hit. New York Times investigation causes internal consternation. On anonymous chat app, employees complain about leadership.   via
Wall Street near session highs on trade whispers. Dow up 0.5% as US and China step up effort to strike G20 truce on trade.

The Wed reversal was discouraging as stocks looked like they would finally be able to bounce after days of selling although session could have been worse, JPM says as SPX ended off the 2746 high but also wound up closing above 2686 low; the peak-to-trough swing was dramatic ~2.1%

Apple mkt cap drops below $900bn following analyst downgrade. Apple's waning iPhone demand means big jump in prices won't be enough, Guggenheim says. iPhone supplier's guidance cuts suggest a 5% drop in 2019 iPhone unit sales, which is larger than the price increase.
The Greek economic recovery looks like this: Greece's banking index drops another 8% despite a bad-loan relief plan. But MSCI removal weighs.
Dow falls >100 points in wild session as Wall St fails to recover from sharp losses.
Fear Index Vix back >20 as investors spooked by tech, GE, Goldman & the rising risk of a recession in 2019. S&P 500 closed down 2%.

Oops! Dow closed >600 points lower driven mainly by weakness in Tech, Financials and General Electric as investors perhaps have become emboldened to sell stocks again, now that the positive catalyst of earnings reports is largely behind us.
Apple tumbles on new signs of weak iPhone demand, company is moving further away from the $1tn mark.

Birth bias: Where mkt goes in your first 10yrs can have impact on how you think about investing for remainder of your life. 5% of all 10y periods saw neg return for S&P 500, 33.8% returns betw 5-10%. We can’t choose which of these buckets we’re born into.

Ouch! Goldman sees S&P 500 profit growth slowing dramatically to 4% in 2020 from 23% this year and revenue growth to drop from 10% this year to 4% in 2020 as benefit of tax cuts dissipates, econ growth slows and margin pressure builds.

Dow closed almost unchg as FOMC meeting offers no surprises. A little-chg statement, no pol action, no new projections, no press conference left mkts’ expectation for a hike in Dec. Only change made to statement was acknowledgment that fixed business investment has moderated.

Asia stocks buoyed by Wall St rally as mkts perfectly adhered to usual post-midterms playbook. S&P 500 went >200d MA for 1st time since Oct19th. Dollar off lows as US 10y yields rise to 3.22% amid improved risk appetite, Oil extends gains on news OPEC and allies discussing cuts.
Dow jumps >500 points after midterms.

Two years in, US President Trump holds stock market bragging rights: S&P 500 has risen 28% since Trump’s election in Nov2016 to the eve of midterm elections. This surpasses performance over same time frame under any other president in the past 64yrs.

Buffett has also demonstrated excellent timing in the sale of equity investments! Berkshire exited stakes in 12 US comps since 2016. 9 have trailed S&P 500 since the end of the quarter in which Buffett finished selling. IBM and GE have been the biggest underperformers. (via BBG)
Apple stock slide continues amid controversy over sales disclosure, iPhone company is moving further away from the $1tn mark.

Signs of profit peak put global stocks at a crossroads: Surging earnings have been the major driver of the Dow industrials’ run this year to 15 records. But many believe the profits bonanza is at an end.

Facing iPhone troubles, Apple tries to change the story: The company plans to stop reporting unit sales, eliminating a performance metric it has provided since the 1980s, as it pushes its services business.

What to do w/ the money? Buffett’s Berkshire Hathaway repurchases >$900mln of it’s stock in Q3, a rare move that indicates Buffett sees dearth of appealing investment options for his comp’s large cash pile. Berkshire hasn’t repurchased shares since 2012.
Now the best time to buy? The S&P 500 has not declined in the 12mths following mid-term election since 1946, SRP says.
Ouch! Apple loses $1 trillion status after soft holiday forecast.

Risk gain momentum on trade deal hopes. Stocks climb, bond yields rise as Trump asked Cabinet to begin drafting deal to signal ceasefire in escalating US-Sino conflict. Yuan jumps beyond 6.90. US 10y rises to 3.17%. In exuberance of optimism, investors dismiss poor Apple figures.
Ouch! Apple briefly falls below $1 trillion market value following weak guidance and and its announcement that it will no longer disclose iPhone, iPad and Mac unit sales.
Apple drops 7% in after-hour trade following disappointing numbers and guidance. Apple will stop reporting unit sales of iPhones, iPads, and Macs beginning in fiscal 2019.
Wall St extends gains as Trump says will meet China's Xi as trade talks 'move along nicely.' BUT sounds engineered to generate an S&P bounce before mid-term elections, Bluebay’s Ash says.

2018 has further advanced the legend of Octobers being difficult, DB says. BUT the typical daily progression of the S&P 500 through the average year using daily data back to 1927 gives hope for a Santa Claus rally after Sep/Oct woes w/ average gains of nearly +3% into Year end.
CitiFX Technicals bearish for markets as monthly reversals have taken place in oil and equities that suggest further losses. Says Dow could fall to 20,428, Brent Oil to $56-$58/bbl.
Dow Jones jumps 241 points, or 1%, paring it’s October drop to 5.1%.
BBG runs a chart which shows how Facebook's daily active users compare to its competitors, at Twitter and Snap.
Peak Facebook: Facebook’s growth of monthly active users is the slowest since as far back as at least 2011, BBG says. Keep in mind that Facebook IPO'ed on May 18, 2012.
Facebook misses revenue forecasts, comes up short on user growth, but earnings top expectations. Shares up almost 2% in after-hours trading.
US stocks ended a tumultuous day sharply higher, with Dow rising 432 points as volatility continues to grip equity markets during earnings season.

Wall St on a roller coaster ride: Dow rallied out of the gate although suffered a meaningful fade from initial high 25040.58 before commencing an aggressive slide that put Dow down to 24122.23, a peak-to-trough swing of ~918 points or ~3.7%. The index bounced to close at 24442.92

Europe stocks bounce w/ all country benchmarks & most sectoral indexes trading firmly in the black. Relief over S&P's rating decision on Italy, some good news from China for autos and strong results from HSBC are lifting sentiment, helping earlier weakness in Asia. (via RTRS)

Italy 10y risk spread drops below 300bps after avoided second downgrade following Moody’s recent change. S&P lowered its outlook on Italy to negative BUT kept the rating unchanged at two notches above junk.   via

Worries about China's slowing econ spread across Asian mkts on Monday w/ US stock futures turning down and Chinese shares in the red as concerns about US corp earnings & global growth continued to hit sentiment. Bonds steady, Italy 10y yields plunge 10bps as S&P kept rating unch.

The Smart Money Index has dropped to lowest since 2009 this week. Is calculated by taking action of the Dow in 2 time periods: the first 30 mins & the close. The first 30 minutes represent emotional buying, driven by greed & fear of the crowd based on good & bad news. (via DB)
S&P strengthens Rome in its fight with Brussels. Rating agency only cut credit outlook but affirms BBB rating. Says Rating constrained by monetary and fiscal inflexibility due to Euro rules.   via

S&P affirms UK's rating at 'AA'; Outlook Negative despite Brexit uncertainties, citing high income levels, diversified econ, strong institutions, & reserve currency status of sterling. Says disorderly Brexit could lead to downgrade as services sector, 3/4 of UK econ could suffer.

S&P gives new food to the Euro-sceptics in Italy. Rating agency says rating constrained by Italy's limited monetary flexibility AND Italy's fiscal flexibility to be more limited in comparison to more dynamic G7 econs such as Canada, Japan, the UK, and the US.

S&P cuts Italy's credit outlook to negative but country avoided 2nd rating downgrade in a week as S&P affirms BBB rating, 2 notches above junk. Says govt's econ and fiscal policy settings are weighing on Italy's econ growth prospects and banks' access to capital market funding.

Another ugly day: Global stock rout deepens w/ S&P 500 joins Nasdaq in correction mode. Google and Amazon results weigh while Europe had its fair share of poor reports too (including BASF, Electrolux, RBS, Valeo). Germany's Dax at 2y lows.

Amazon shares tumble almost 9% in after-hours trading on disappointing forecast for holiday revenue. Comp's overall top line for Q3 rose 29% YoY to $56.6bn but flubbed Wall Street’s expectations too. But Amazon’s ad initiative is proving useful.
The S&P 500 may not yet be in correction territory, but most stocks are already in correction or bear market.

Wall St hit hard but major indices were able to bounce enormously from the lows (the SPX was down ~64 points or ~2.3% at the low but finished the day down ~15 points). BUT The main problem remains a breach in the earnings firewall, JPM says.
Dow plunges >500points in ugly global risk off move.
Sea of red: Wall Street follows global stock mkts lower in Risk Off trade. Dow drops sharply in early trading as two industrial giants warn of trouble.
This chart suggests that S&P500 has to fall 20% as CenBank liquidity will dry up. (Chart via Standard Chartered)

"Long FAANG+BAT" (Facebook, Amazon, Apple, Netflix, Google + Baidu, Alibaba, Tencent) remains the most crowded trade for 9th straight month in BofAML Fund Manager Survey; note August reading was most crowded trade outright since Long USD Dec '15.

Asia stocks edge up but Saudi tensions limit gains. China lower after S&P report warning over off-balance sheet local govt debts. Crude oil rises amid US-Saudi discord over missing journalist. 10y US yields rise to 3.17%. Yen, Franc, Gold supported by recent risk aversion.

The fall of Italy in one chart: By end of Oct two agencies are supposed to review Italy’s rating – S&P on 26 Oct and Moody’s by end of month. Moody’s – historically more bearish on peripheral countries – placed Italy's rating under review for downgrade on 25 May. (via Nomura)

S&P 500 falls 2.1% to lowest level since Jul. Has longest streak of declines since Nov. 2016. There wasn‘t any actual news but markets are still in the midst of a vicious correction that obviously has yet to run its course.

Wall Street tumbled the most since Feb as fresh concern about the impact of the trade war with China roiled technology and industrial shares. Dow Jones Industrial dropped 832 points. Margin calls could trigger a bigger sell-off.
Fear Index Vix jumps as S&P500 craters. 'Stocks in full selloff mode w/ a fair smattering of fear,' Neil Wilson from   says.
Stocks sink most since June on trade, yield angst. S&P 500 in longest slump since Nov2016, the era Trump. Puts are flying, BBG reports.

Speed matters: When rates rise too far, too fast (2+ standard deviations above normal rate of change or ~40bp) then S&P 500 returns have typically been negative, Goldman says. Past days appears to have taken rates over speed limit for most investor's comfort. S&P 500 dropped 1%.

Amazon to raise its minimum US wage to $15 an hour. New level starts Nov1. “We listened to our critics, thought hard about what we wanted to do, and decided we want to lead,” said Amazon CEO Jeff Bezos.

Asia stocks slip as NAFTA lift fades; oil near 4y highs. MSCI Asia-Pacific index falls almost 1%, Nikkei is bucking the trend. China’s markets are shut throughout the week. Dollar trades higher. Bonds and Bitcoin steady.

Blowout Quarter for stocks has Mom and Pop all in, Pros cautious. S&P 500 surged 7.2% in the 3mnths ended Friday as cash holdings at broker accounts slide to record lows. Strategist forecasts imply worst fourth quarter since 2012.

Stocks in Asia gain ahead of Fed meeting. Fed updated projections may set expectations for 2019, show neutral interest rate and highlight whether there is such a thing as a Powell put. China stocks hit 8 week high, as MSCI considers lifting index weightings. Brent hits 4y high.
Ouch! Instagram founders leave Facebook after clashes with Mark Zuckerberg over the product's direction, sources say. Facebook shares have already underperformed this year among the FANG bucket.

Good Morning from Germany where the stock mkt index Dax suffers from falling P/E (-7%) and lacklustre EPS trend (only +3%y/y). Dax is 15ppts behind the S&P this year as S&P 500 has become an earnings-driven bull market. EPS trend has improved by a whopping 23% y/y.

S&P ups Australia's AAA credit outlook from neg to stable despite housing bubble, delivering an econ win following months of pol turmoil for Coalition govt. BUT ratings could come under pressure if house prices fall sharply and increase risks to fiscal accounts & fin stability.
Bull market back in sync as Dow finally eclipses Jan high. All major US benchmarks have now fully erased February losses. While a dose of confidence, the late comeback shows trade risk.
Nein, Sie können beruhigt sein: Amazon bleibt eine großartige Geschichte. Selbst eine Zerschlagung in Amazon Web Services und einen Amazon Internethändler würde wohl Werte heben!

Selten habe ich mit Deffner so heftig & lautstark diskutiert. Es geht darum, ob der mit 162 Mrd.$ reichste Mensch der Welt, Amazon-Chef Bezos, Gutmensch oder Gutsherr ist und ob die Türkei am Rande des Abgrunds steht? Hören, teilen, abonnieren!   via

Asia shares on slippery slope as US-China showdown on trade escalates. Strong Dollar and rising Treasury yields after very strong US NFPs didn't help. US Fed expected to raise later this mnth. Tech is continuing to sell off, w/ weakness in Apple Supply Chain. Gold & Bitcoin drop.

Good morning from Germany, the 4th largest economy in the world, but a developing country when it comes to stock market. Total German stock mkt capitalization amounts to only $2.26tn, lower than the combined market value of US's Top3 stocks Apple, Amazon and Microsoft of $2.86tn

Facebook and Twitter are under pressure from US lawmakers to explain how their systems work and how they spot material that needs removed. US Justice Department probes whether social media is 'stifling' speech.

Goldman joins Citigroup in flashing warnings on S&P 500. Wall Street’s voices of concern over stocks getting louder. Citi’s sentiment model signals higher chance of stock losses. Goldman says investors should be prepared for lower returns in coming years.

Amazon followed Apple to become the second U.S. company to reach $1 trillion in stock-market value, reflecting the online retailer’s striking transformation from a profitless bookseller into a disruptive force of commerce.

FANGMAN complex hit another life-time high despite Facebook and Netflix trade way below their highs on the back of mixed results. So after all the talk about Tech stock trepidation, mega-cap Tech was still a good place to be for the summer, Goldman says.

Good morning from Germany, which is lagging behind terribly in the stock market. Half the Dax Index consists of problem cases: Deutsche Bank, Bayer, Car comps, Utility sector, Conti, ThyssenKrupp. The Dax has dropped 4% this year while the S&P 500 has gained almost 10% since Jan
Emerging Markets currencies bounce despite more negative news. Argentina's B+ may be cut by S&P, which cited a weak fiscal and external profile, limited monetary flexibility and growing debt burden.

Asia stocks fail to follow record rally on Wall St as weakness in China outweighs NAFTA trade optimism. S&P 500, Nasdaq climb to fresh all-time highs. China mood sours after Trump’s broadsides against Chinese currency practices. Dollar steady & US Treasury yields almost unchg.

Dow Jones Industrial closed at fresh all-time highs >26k as the formal announcement of US-Mexico trade deal prompted a broad-based Risk-On rotation w/ industrials, materials, financials, and tech leading the way on the upside while bond proxies lagged.

`Amazon effect' may make Central Bank job harder, Jackson Hole paper highlights. Online competition has made prices more susceptible to shocks. Average duration of prices fell as share of online sales rose.

S&P500 rose to an all-time high following Fed Chair's remarks at Jackson Hole that lead to flattening of 2s10s yield spread <20bp. Powell supported gradual pace of rate increases while stating that he doesn't see signs of elevated risk of overheating from an inflation standpoint.
Current US bull mkts may one of longest in US history, BUT the S&P 500 advance since March 2009 hasn't been that impressive in post-World War II terms. (via BBG)
Failed bounce: Facebook investors who bought the historic dip aren’t seeing a quick recovery. Only FAANG stock in the red in 2018.

The longest bull market in US equities may end in 2019, Capital Economics says. Expects S&P500 will end next year at 2,300. This would be a fall of almost exactly 20% from its peak. If so, the bull market would then be all but over.

Today, the S&P 500's bull-market run will turn 3,453 days old, which will make it the longest such streak in history. Bull run overtakes 3,452 days between November 1990 and March 2000, according to S&P Dow Jones indices.

Asia shares edge up w/ sentiment boosted by Wall Street's intraday record for the S&P500, but fragile China retreated. Developments in US politics that saw Trump's former lawyer Cohen plead guilty soured mood a bit. Dollar slipped & US Treasuries little changed. Bitcoin >$6.7k.

In Moody's view, the probability that the Turkish authorities will manage to engineer a "soft landing" of economy is declining in the context of weakened institutions & increasing tensions w/ US. S&P expects Turkey to fall into recession next year.
S&P says it forecasts a recession next year for Turkey.
Turkey rating cut to B+ from BB- by S&P, outlook stable. Says substantial weakening of the Liea has neg fiscal implications.
Hedge Fund legend George Soros bets again big against Wall Street and Donald Trump. He has doubled his SPDR S&P500 put positions to 2.3mln.   via

Long FAANG+BAT (Facebook, Amazon, Apple, Netflix, Google + Baidu, Alibaba, Tencent) remains the most crowded trade for 7th straight month in BofAML Fund Manager Survey and most crowded trade outright since Long USD Dec'15.

Russia Ruble plunges >3% as US is imposing new sanctions on Russia, on allegations that Moscow tried to assassinate former Russian spy & UK citizen, Sergei Skripal. This is not only talk of sanctions. Another bill incl measures to sanction new govt debt & block USD transactions.

Gary Cohn believes Facebook is more dangerous than banks before the financial crisis, due to their dissemination of misinformation: ‚I think banks were more responsible citizens in ’08 than some of the social media companies are today.‘

The question of which stock would be 1st to reach $1tn stock mkt cap was answered last week as Apple gained 9%, Goldman says. But investors should focus on a different $1 trillion number that will have a key influence total buyback authorizations likely to be announced this year.

Apple wins race to be first trillion-dollar company 4 decades after it was co-founded by Steve Jobs in a Silicon Valley garage & later revolutionized the worlds of computing, music & mobile communications. Shares closed at $207.39, propelling market value to $1.002tn. (via BBG)
Apple wins race to be first trillion-dollar company. BUT Apple isn't the 1st stock to take a shot at $1 trillion. PetroChina crossed milestone back in Nov2007.
Apple share gains push company to $1 trillion milestone.

Apple’s $1tn market value is a moving target as number of outstanding shares keeps falling w/ record buyback programme. Despite latest share price jump >200 Dollar following upbeat earnings, the market cap is only at $973bn.
Apple shares have been trailing behind the FAANG’s this year, BBG reports. But after last week's tech rout, the gap is shrinking.

Apple shares up about 3% after results as comp beats w/ Q318 report: Revenues of $53.3bn, above forecasts of $52.4bn. EPS of $2.34 vs. $2.18 exp. But iPhone sales slight miss w/ 41.3M, est. 41.6M. At post-mkt high of $196 current mkt cap at $949.2bn, shy of $1tn mark. (via BBG)
TM stands for trademark, Tesla is part of the index as well as Twitter, Alibaba, Badiu, Apple alongside FANG!
Tech sell-off continues w/ FANGMAN loses another 1.7% in mkt cap. Combined value of Facebook, Amazon, Netflix, Google, Apple, NVidia now down almost $300bn since last week's high.

Asia stocks fall in a soggy start to the week as investors questioned earnings results against lofty expectations after Facebook, Twitter, Intel & prepared for key CenBank meetings. Focus on Tue's BoJ amid talk of policy tweaks. Yuan dropped to 1y low driven by China pol easing.
Move over FANGs, make way for MAGA: Microsoft, Apple, Google and Amazon are taking the market higher.

Global stocks have gained $820bn in mkt cap this week in which Facebook, Twitter, EA, and Nielsen all lost 10%-25% of their value, all of US car makers cut their guidance and we learned that new home sales fell by 5% in Jul. But EU-US trade truce and decent US GDP numbers help.

Patience is wearing thin w/ tech stocks this earnings season. Facebook suffered worst battering in the history of U.S. stocks. Intel, which topped all forecasts, had $20bn wiped from its value. Netflix plunged even though its net income sextupled.
Who will be the first $ 1 trillion company? Shares of Amazon have climbed 56% this year, putting comp on track for a trillion-dollar valuation. But Google and Apple are still ahead.

Facebook shocked investors by revealing disappointing second-quarter earnings and forecasts. Shares tumbled >20%, wiping up to $140bn off the company’s value, in one of the largest after-market drops ever.

Asia share gains fade after US-EU trade optimism as US-China trade worries linger and crash in Facebook shares highlights risk in current earnings season. Euro holds gains >$1.17. 10y Japan yields jump to 1y high on BoJ bets.
Ouch! This BBG chart shows the decline in Facebook’s monthly active user growth!

Facebook shares crash in after-hours trading, wiping out $6.7bn from Zuckerberg's net worth. FB reported slower-than-expected revenue growth in Q2 as user growth miss estimates, indicating the social-media website felt some effects from series of controversies over past mths.

Asia stocks gain following stellar numbers from Google. Even Yuan drop to fresh 1y low couldn't spoil the party. US 10y yields hold just below 3% while bond sell-off in Japan has stopped ahead of BoJ pol decision on July 31. Dollar steady, Bitcoin on the cusp of $8k.
FAANGs are up on Google's earnings beat. Google parent company Alphabet reported Q2 sales of $26.24bn vs $25.55bn expetcted. Google’s advertising business grew a whopping 24%.

In case you missed it: S&P affirms Russia at BBB- (one notch above junk), stable outlook citing solid external and public balance sheets, coupled w/ a flexible exchange rate and prudent fiscal framework. BUT sanctions and weak institutions constrain growth prospects.
Dow Gold Ratio has risen to 20.4, highest level since 2007.
Google to be fined €4.3bn by EU in Android antitrust case, equals to 0.6% of current mkt cap. The fine would top the EU’s €2.4bn antitrust decision against Google just over a year ago.
Amazon continues to catch up w/ Apple in race to first $1trillion mkt cap company. As Amazon hit fresh high on Monday, AAPL's $937bn market cap now leads AMZN's by only ~$45bn.

This chart highlights that US is weathering trade war, rest of the world less so. S&P 500 holding up relatively better than some other global indexes amid this trade spat. Chinese stock market is the biggest loser. (via Strategas)
Guess when the German Dax lost it's edge over Dow & Co. In 2015! Since then German politics have become bumpy and the social capital has started to twindle.

Ouch! 2018 saw the worst first-half of a year for global stocks since 2010 as a mix of US-China trade tensions, central banks turning off the money taps and cooling growth in Europe wiped a trillion dollars off MSCI's 47-country world index, RTRS says.

Netflix is eating TV: Morgan Stanley gets bearish on European TV networks & moves 5 stocks to "underweight", incl a double downgrade of ProSiebenSat.1. Says subscription Video on demand, particularly by Netflix & Amazon, depresses linear viewing and ad revenue growth. (via RTRS)

Global equity sell-off ran out of steam in Asia as investors see kind of 'Trump Put'. Trade advisor Navarro tries to calm investors, says market movement that saw Dow fall nearly 500 points was "an overreaction." US Treasury yields steady. Euro >$1.17. Bitcoin stable at $6.2k.

Greece raised to B+ by S&P; Outlook to Stable from positive. Believes that creation of liquidity buffers & additional debt maturity extensions ahead of the Greece’s graduation from ESM program significantly reduces sovereign debt servicing risks over the next 2yrs.
Fear index VIX jumps by 26% on trade worries w/ S&P 500 fell most since Apr.

Asia stocks hit 6mth lows following Risk-Off move on Wall St. S&P500 suffered worst session since May as hints of weakness in both micro guidance (Daimler) & macro surveys (Philly Fed) suggest that tariffs take econ toll. Oil higher ahead of crucial Opec meeting. US10y ylds >2.9%
Volatility has returned with a vengeance as Fed continues to shrink balance sheet. Number of days the S&P 500 rose or fell >1% is sharply up this year.

General Electric, an original member of the Dow that has been a member of the 30-stock index continuously since 1907, will be removed from the Dow Jones Industrial Average in the latest setback for the firm.

US stocks are understandably coming for sale as investors respond to latest salvos in the US-China trade battle. Dow Jones gives up 2018 gains as Trump threatens to hit China w/$200bn in new tariffs. Problem is more absence of buyers rather than rush of selling pressure, JPM says
Oops! For 1st time in 10yrs, 2y US yield 20bp above S&P 500 div yield, CBK says. Hover the last 25yrs the average yield gap has been 80bp higher at 100bp.

Ouch! Hedge got squeezed most of the times in the past year. Thomson Reuters Most Shorted Index has gained 25% since Jun 2017 vs an S&P 500 rise of ~14%. Shares in some heavily shorted stocks rallied Monday w/Tesla, Chipotle, Hertz, Avis Budget seeing strong gains.

Asia stocks shrug off G7 fallout as focus shifts from divisive G7 meeting to historic Trump-Kim summit. MSCI Asia Pacific index up 0.2% as investors awaiting Fed, ECB and BoJ decisions later this week. Dollar, Gold, Bonds steafy in one of the most important weeks of the year.

This chart highlights how far Europe is behind. Technology is dominated by the US & China. The S&P has 25% in Tech, China is now over 40%. Europe has just 5% of its market capitalisation in the Tech sector (almost 50% of which is comprised of just 2comps: SAP, ASML, Goldman says.

Good morning from Germany which is now smaller than the current size of Big Tech. FAAMG stocks (Facebook, Amazon, Apple, Microsoft and Google) have a combined market capitalisation of $3.8tn greater than German GDP of $3.7tn. (Map which compares tech giants to GDP via Goldman)

FANGMAN stocks hit fresh highs as investors continue to lean into secular winners 8yrs into current econ expansion. Amazon has crossed $800bn mkt cap for 1st time. Tech returns have been justified by fundamental growth, valuations much lower compared w/prev bubbles, Goldman says

Nasdaq climbs to record in the latest sign that investors questioning the global growth story are funneling their money into shares of fast-growing companies. Nasdaq is up 10.2% ytd, w/ heavyweights like Amazon, Apple, Microsoft all up double-digit.

It's totally absurd. With Italy & Spain, the 3rd and 4th largest economies in the eurozone have new governments that threaten the stability of the currency union, but 10y yields in Italy and Spain have dropped 7 rsp 2bps today.
Deutsche Bank share price stabilizes despite S&P downgrade after CEO letter.

Ouch! Deutsche Bank credit rating was cut by S&P Global Ratings by one notch to BBB+ from A-, the ratings company said in a statement Friday. The downgrade is a blow to new CEO Christian Sewing as he tries to reinvigorate Europe’s largest investment bank.

Global stocks have lost €500bn in mkt cap this week as rising oil & yields unnerve investors. Real US yields of almost 1% becoming a competition for equities. Rate-sensitive stocks & Tech lagged this week w/several FANGMAN stocks underperforming, incl Google, Nvidia, & Facebook.
No, it's in German, but it's worth to learn German to hear it! And of course, you can leave us 5* on Apple iTunes.
Oops! Investors spooked by jumping yields. Dow Jones is taking a hit as 10y US Treasury yields rising to 3.05% after retail data reignited inflation fears.

Global stocks have gained $900bn in mkt cap this week on return of Goldilocks (mix of benign inflation & decent growth). End to earnings season (one that was characterized by more beats & fewer misses than usual), & higher oil helped to put S&P500 back in pos territory for 2018.

Barron’s bullish for stocks citing financial engineering. Stock buybacks to hit fresh record of $650bn this yr. Offer investors effective yield of 3%, calculated by dividing repurchases by $23tn mkt value of S&P500. Combine w/2% dividend yield, investors should get 5% yld in 2018
Apple hits fresh life-time high after credit card deal w/ Goldman Sachs. NOW on course to become the first real $1tn company.
Dow gains for a 6th consecutive day as Goldlocks narrative returns after soft US inflation data. Dow now again break-even for the year.

Apple isn't the 1st stock to take a shot at $1 trillion. PetroChina crossed milestone back in Nov2007, when its mainland shares almost tripled in value in their Shanghai trading debut. But state-controlled energy comp dropped below that level within a day
The FAANG stocks have set another record: The block of Facebook, Amazon, Apple, Netflix and Google now account for >27% of the NASDAQ Composite, a new all-time high.
Bitcoin drops as Buffett compared bitcoin to rat poison at Berkshire Hathaway's annual meeting. 87-year-old investor said bitcoin would "definitely come to a bad ending."

Creative destruction is accelerating: S&P 500 lifespans continue to shrink. The 33y average tenure of companies on the S&P 500 in 1964 narrowed to 24yrs by 2016 and is forecast to shrink to just 12yrs by 2027.
Big Tech stages comeback as Apple hit an all-time high after Buffett's Berkshire Hathaway disclosed it had bought 75mln more shares of the iPhone maker in Q1 2018. FANGMAN near record.
The most important chart in the world: Google encapsulates everything about the current age where we are in the market,  says. A must hear podcast.
Turkey Lira sell-off accelerates after S&P downgrade.
Turkey 10y yields jump as spending pledge ahead of Jun24 election adds to deficit concern and S&P downgrade soured sentiment.
Turkey Lira continues falling BUT takes downgrade relatively well. Erased some of the initial losses after S&P cut rating deeper into junk.
Apple stocks jump >3% in after-hours as company adding $100bn to its stock-buyback plans.

Ouch! S&P lowers Turkey rating to BB- from BB; outlook to stable from negative citing macroeconomic imbalances, mainly a deterioraring current account and fiscal deficit. Says could lower rating if ext financing, Lira detoriate further.

A full-blown trade war between EU & US would be extremely costly for EU compas. S&P estimates that 23% of revenues for investment grade comps are derived from US, w/health care, business & consumer services, media, and hotels, restaurants and leisure having the largest exposure.

While US trade deficit w/China is the largest single element of this trade imbalance, the deficit w/EU as a whole ranks second and is greater in value than that w/Mexico. Within EU, Germany ($66bn), Italy ($33bn) & France ($15bn) are the 3 largest deficit contributors. (via S&P)

Jeff Bezos reveals what it’s like to build an empire and become the richest man in the world — and why unconditional love is so important for taking risk. My boss at Axel Springer had an very interesting conversation w/Amazon CEO Bezos.

Asia stocks posting modest gains on earnings boost from Amazon, Baidu, Intel but off the highs on caution into trade negotiations & the long weekend. Mkts in Seoul underpinned by optimism as leaders of N. & S.Korea held their first summit in over a decade. Bonds rally. US 10y <3%

Good morning from Germany where the whole machinery sector invests less money in their future than US tech giant Google. In times of Industry 4.0 (the era of the robot), Silicon valley threatens tech leadership of German engineering firms.   via
Amazon's Bezos just had a banner day. His fortune rose $12bn on Thursday if you factored in extended trading, taking his net worth to $134bn, BBG reports.

Amazon surprised investors by more than doubling its quarterly profits to $1.6bn, continuing its streak of fiscal discipline. Share jumped more than 6% in after-hours trading, poised to open at a new record tomorrow.

Ouch! Short sellers stung by Facebook’s upbeat earnings report, IHS says. While short demand for FB up over 25% this year, there has been some notable covering over last week w/over 5m shares returned. Short interest number currently shows 32m shares but was collected for Apr13th

Facebook extends gain in after hours following bullish call. Sandberg had explained that there's no need to worry about business models beyond advertising. Even just porting all Facebook advertisers over to Instagram would be huge. And then there's Messenger, WhatsApp...

Facebook shares jumps 4.6% in after hours trading as ad sales near records and users keep flocking to the social network despite data scandal and the comp will do some financial engineering w/ additional share buyback programme.

With US 10y yield hitting 3% for first time in 4yrs, Value showing relative strength vs Growth: iShares S&P 500 Value / iShares S&P 500 Growth ETF ratio hitting highest level since mid-Feb. (via RTRS)

FAANG divorced: Facebook, Amazon, Apple, Netflix and Google have tended to move together in the past, but of late their fortunes have diverged: Amazon up 33% ytd, Google and Apple have chalked up single-digit gains, Netflix up whopping 72% but Facebook has fallen 6%.

Amazon is eating the world: More than 100 million people globally are now paying for Amazon Prime, a sign of how Amazon has used the service to evolve from an online marketplace that struggled with profitability into an e-commerce powerhouse.
The FANG trade doesn't need Facebook. Tech stocks roaring back to life after an upbeat earnings report from Netflix - with or without Facebook.

Recession indicator keeps worsening. US 2s10s yield spread hits another decade low at 42bps. Its especially notable given the stock strength. S&P500 extended recent rally w/ index up >1% and up through both 50d and 100d MA.

Good morning from US where nearly 1/3rd of Americans (54mln people) believe Facebook has "neg impact on society." That makes Facebook less of a societal ill than Marlboro but worse than McDonald’s fast food. Poll conducted in Feb, before Cambridge scandal
Totally absurd! S&P revises outlook of nearly bankrupt Japan to positive from stable. Japan's Debt to GDP ratio has quadrupled to 240% in the last 3 decades.

Global stocks gain as focus shifts from trade (macro) to decent earnings (micro). Decoupling of stocks from earnings has never persisted for more than 1quarter, JPM says. Over past 25yrs, there have only been 16quarters when US earnings have grown y/y & S&P delivered neg returns.
Apple is the biggest company in the world but one of the least oligarchy. Art Levinson is only insider known to have at least $1bn.
Facebook's China argument is revealed in Zuckerberg's Congress hearing notes.

Xi bump: US futures rose after China President Xi Jinping pledged greater openness in response to escalating trade disputes w/ the U.S in a speech that also warned against returning to a “Cold War mentality”. S&P 500 futures jumped as much as 1.5% while markets in Asia also rose.

Short sellers have been taking action in Tech sector, IHS reports, increasing bets against Facebook: Since last exchange short interest was collected for settlement on March 15th, we’ve seen a further 7m shares go on loan. IHS expects that next exchange number will print higher.
Big quarter seen for Corporate America w/ expectations that tax cuts will help S&P 500 to show its biggest quarterly profit growth in seven years.
